text: R E S E A R C H A R T I C L E Solid phase microextraction as a powerful alternative for screening of secondary metabolites in actinomycetes Vinicius Ricardo Acquaro Junior1 | Júlia Pereira Rodrigues2 | Luiz Alberto Beraldo Moraes2 1 Instituto de Química de São Carlos, Universidade de São Paulo, São Paulo, Brazil 2 Departamento de Química, Faculdade de Filosofia Ciências e Letras de Ribeirão Preto, Universidade de São Paulo, São Paulo, Brazil Correspondence Dr. Luiz Alberto Beraldo Moraes, Departamento de Química, Faculdade de Filosofia Ciências e Letras de Ribeirão Preto, Universidade de São Paulo, São Paulo, Bandeirantes Avenida, 3900, Monte Alegre, 14040‐901 Ribeirão Preto, São Paulo, Brasil. Email: luizmoraes@ffclrp.usp.br Funding information Conselho Nacional de Desenvolvimento Científico e Tecnológico, Grant/Award Num- ber: 14195620186; Coordenação de Aperfeiçoamento de Pessoal de Nível Superior, Grant/Award Number: 001; FAPESP, Grant/ Award Numbers: 2016/22023‐0 and 2018/ 03956‐1 J Mass Spectrom. 2019;1–11. Actinobacteria are one of the most promising producers of medically and industrially relevant secondary metabolites. However, screening of such compounds in actinobacteria growth demands simple, fast, and efficient extraction procedures that enable detection and precise quantification of biologically active compounds. In this regard, solid phase microextraction (SPME) emerges as an ideal extraction technique for screening of secondary metabolites in bacteria culture due to its non‐exhaustive, minimally invasive, and non‐destructive nature: workflow; balanced coverage feature; metabolism quenching capabilities; and supe- rior cleanup, as well as its versatility in configuration, which enables automation

and high throughput applications. The current work provides a comparison of micro‐scale and direct immersion SPME (DI‐SPME) for screening of secondary metab- olites, describes the optimization of the developed DI‐SPME method, and introduces the developed technique for mapping of target secondary metabolites as well as its direct coupling to mass spectrometry for such applications. The optimized DI‐SPME method provided higher amounts of extracted ions and intensity signals, yielding superior extraction and desorption efficiency as compared with micro‐scale extrac- tion. Studied compounds presented stability on the coating for 24 h at room temper- ature. The DI‐SPME mapping approach revealed that lysolipin I and the lienomycin analog are distributed along the center and edges of the colony, respectively. Direct coupling of SPME to MS provided a similar ions profile as SPME‐LC‐MS while enabling a significant decrease in analysis time, demonstrating its suitability for such applications. DI‐SPME is herein presented as an alternative to micro‐scale extraction for screening of secondary metabolites in actinobacteria solid medium, as well as a feasible alternative to DESI‐IMS for mapping of biologic radial distribution of second- ary metabolites and cell life cycle studies. Lastly, the direct coupling of DI‐SPME to MS is presented as a fast, powerful technique for high throughput analysis of second- ary metabolites in this medium. solid‐phase microextraction, secondary metabolites, screening, mapping, direct analysis wileyonlinelibrary.com/journal/jms its integrated sample preparation © 2019 John Wiley & Sons, Ltd. The phylum Actinobacteria is composed of phylogenetically and phys- iologically diverse bacteria known to play a key role in maintaining Earth's ecosystems.1 Their most essential contributions stem from the production of secondary metabolites involved in a wide range of biological activities.2 Various biological functions served by secondary metabolites have been studied to date, including their properties as antibiotics, anticancer, antitumor, and immunosuppressive agents.3,4 However, efficient screening of secondary metabolites demands the use of fast and simple extraction methods capable of circumventing losses of biologically active compounds.4-7 large number of cultures. In this regard, many HPLC methods have

been described for specific determinations of metabolites. As a simple screening method, Filtenborg et al. first introduced the plug extraction method in 1983.8 This method was later modified by Smedsgaard in 19979 and introduced as the micro‐scale extraction procedure. Since then, micro‐scale has been adopted as a standard method for screen- ing of metabolites in solid culture media.10-12 scale extraction method have made it a renowned technique for screening of secondary metabolites. The destructive nature of the extraction method hinders resampling and complementary analyses of the same sample via other methods, limiting its suitability for a number of appli- cations. Likewise, the non‐selectivity of the micro‐sampling method may result in a large number of extracted interferences, consequently affecting analytical signal strength, and, thus, the qualitative and quan- titative performance of the method. SPME is a non‐destructive, equilibrium‐based extraction technique that extracts very low, often negligible amounts of compounds present in the sample.13 These fea- tures allow for monitoring of chemical changes, partition equilibria, and speciation of compounds due to the minimum perturbation caused to the sample system.14 SPME has been employed in a broad number of applications encompassing diverse fields of study, including various biological,15,16 environmental,17,18 food,19,20 and forensic applications,21,22 among others. Among the many advantages imparted by SPME that have made it a technique of choice for a large number of applications, the widespread use of SPME is largely attributed to the versatile nature of the technique, which offers a wide variety of geometries and coat- ings chemistries, as well as superior instrument compatibility.13 In

addition, SPME can be used for both untargeted and targeted analysis due to its “balance coverage” feature and unique tuning abilities, Secondary metabolites profile studies often involve screening of a Undoubtedly, the simplicity and swiftness afforded by the micro‐ As an alternative capable of addressing the above limitations, solid its non‐selective and destructive nature, which allow for optimization of applications for analysis of specific compounds or classes of compounds, as well as for untargeted inves- tigations covering a wide range of compounds of diverse physico- chemical properties and polarities.13,23-25 Although SPME has been previously mislabeled as an extraction technique limited by low ana- lyte recoveries and long extraction times, recent studies have been demystifying these beliefs.13,16 achieving superior enrichment factors as it enables preconcentration of analytes on the extraction phase while only utilizing low volumes of solvent for desorption, thus enabling trace level analysis applica- tions at limits of detection/limits of quantification (LODs/LOQs) com- parable with traditional exhaustive extraction techniques (i.e. part per billion and part per trillion). In addition, the development of different geometries and configurations of SPME has allowed for direct cou- pling of the technique to various detection systems. Indeed, SPME has been successfully coupled to MS, enabling high‐throughput appli- cations that circumvent the need for the time‐consuming chromatog- raphy separation step.13,26 ple preparation method are crucial factors in securing a representative composition of metabolites present in bacteria culture. SPME enables direct extraction of metabolites while integrating sampling, sample preparation, and metabolism quenching in a single step.15,27 Beyond simplifying the analysis workflow and reducing the introduction of possible sources of errors and contaminations, the extractive nature of SPME also enables negligible depletion and non‐sample withdrawal (i.e. in vivo or on‐site), thus circumventing perturbations to the living system under study that would undoubtedly change its metabolic pro- file. Together with the metabolism quenching step inherent of SPME, these unique properties of SPME significantly reduce the risk of

changes in metabolome composition in comparison with other methods, thus enabling extraction of short‐lived or unstable metabo- lites not otherwise detectable via traditional methods.13,15,27 SPME has been successfully applied in the headspace of bacteria cultures to analyze fatty acid methyl esters (FAMEs)28 and volatile organic compounds ,29,30 volatile metabolome analysis,23,31 as well as for direct immersion SPME (DI‐SPME).32,33 However, to the best of these authors' knowledge, the feasibility of directly inserting SPME fibers into bacteria culture for analysis of non‐volatile compounds has yet to be comprehensively reported in the literature. Therefore, the currently presented study aimed at assessing the potential of DI‐SPME for screening of secondary metabolites in actinobacteria culture. A comparison of micro‐scale and DI‐SPME was herein undertaken by taking into account factors such as the amounts of ions extracted, the magnitude signals attained for bacteria culture and blank extractions, organic solvent use, and the respective sample preparation workflows of each technique. Furthermore, this work included optimization of the method for two target secondary use of an experimental design approach for desorption solvent optimi- zation. vided by the Collection of Microorganisms for Agricultural and Environmental Importance (CCMA, EMBRAPA, Brazil) 34 The culture medium PDA (potato dextrose agar) and ISP‐2 were obtained from Sigma‐Aldrich (Sigma‐Aldrich Corporation, St. Louis, USA). Petri plates (100 × 15 mm) and Eppendorf tubes (2 ml) were purchased from Fisher Scientific (Fisher Scientific International, Inc., PA, USA). ethyl acetate, and water were acquired from Fisher Scientific (Fisher Scientific International, Inc., PA, USA). Formic acid was obtained from Sigma‐Aldrich (Sigma‐Aldrich Corporation, St. Louis, USA). Nitinol wires were cut at a length of 10 cm then coated using a slurry with hydrophilic–lipophilic balance (HLB) particles (5 μm) mixed with poly- acrylonitrile (PAN), as described by Gómez‐Ríos et al..35 The extractive phase of the fiber was consisted of a coating thickness of 25 μm and a length of 5 mm. The HLB particles utilized in this procedure were sourced from an Oasis HLB online column (3 × 20 mm, 5 μm; Waters 2.2 | Preparation of bacteria culture The actinobacteria preparation procedure was carried out in accordance to previously published work by Rodrigues et al.36 Briefly, actinobacteria Caat 1‐54 (glycerol stock) was fermented in an Erlenmeyer flask (125 ml) prefilled with 25 ml of autoclaved ISP‐2 cul- ture medium. The solid fermentation process was left to take place overnight (16–18 h) at 37°C. Following the conclusion of the fermenta- tion process, a single spore was transferred to a petri plate with an autoclaved PDA culture medium through a 1000‐μl pipette tip. The petri plate was then incubated at 37°C for 14 d. 2.3 | Micro‐scale experimental procedure The micro‐scale method previously described by Smedsgaard9 was carried out with some modifications. Plugs of actinobacteria culture

measuring 6 mm (i.d) were cut from the center to the corner of the petri dish. Individual plugs were then transferred to an Eppendorf tube (2 ml), whereupon 1 ml of extraction solvent (ethyl acetate/methanol, 70:30—v/v) was added, and the resulting mixture sonicated (30 min). Subsequently, the supernatant was collected and dried under a N2 stream (30 min). Lastly, the extract was reconstituted in 100 μl of The LC‐MS grade solvents acetonitrile (ACN), methanol (MeOH), the initial composition of the mobile phase and 10 μl injected into the liquid chromatography‐diode array detector‐tandem mass spec- trometer (LC‐DAD‐MS) system. 2.4 | DI‐SPME experimental procedure DI‐SPME extraction was performed by directly immersing SPME fibers into the actinobacteria culture. Extraction time profiles, desorption time profiles, stability assessments, and solvent composition optimiza- tion were carried out for lysolipin I and the lienomycin analog due to their biological activity, as previously reported.36,37 A preconditioned fiber was inserted into the crude extract (static extraction) for 60 min then subsequently rinsed in a glass vial containing 300 μl of ultra‐pure water for 5 s so as to facilitate the removal of potentially interfering compounds adhered to the coating surface. Subsequently, desorption of extracted compounds was carried out by placing the fiber into 100 μl of a methanol/acetonitrile/water solution (50:25:25, v/v/v) inside a glass insert for a 30‐min period. Finally, 10 μl of the desorption solution was injected into the LC‐DAD‐MS system. The desorption solution utilized in the SPME method was opti- mized via simplex‐centroid design (SCD). SCD was performed consid- ering three solvents (methanol, acetonitrile, and water) and 10 experiments in total. Final SCD data was processed by Statistica soft- ware 12.0 (TIBCO StatisticaTM, CA, USA).

Extracted compounds were analyzed on a Water Acquity UPLC H‐ Class system coupled to a tandem mass spectrometer Xevo TQ‐S™ (Waters Corporation, MA, USA) with a Z‐spray ion source in positive and negative mode. Chromatography separation was carried out in reverse mode using an Ascentis Express F5 Column (10 cm × 2.1mm, 2.7 μm). Separation was performed in gradient mode, starting with 90% of A (acetonitrile with 0.1% formic acid) and 10% of B (ultra- pure water with 0.1% formic acid), decreasing to 10% of A within 12 min, and returning to initial conditions within 15 min at a 0.5 ml min−1 flow rate. MS operating parameters were optimized as follows: source temperature of 120°C, desolvation temperature of 300 °C, desolvation gas flow of 500 L h−11 (N2, 99.9% purity), cone gas flow of 20 L h−1 (N2, 99.9% purity), and capillary and cone voltage of 3.2 kV and 60 V in positive mode and −3.2 kV and −60 V in negative mode, respectively. Full scan mode was carried out from m/z 100 to 1400 using a cycle scan of 0.3 s. The diode array detector (DAD) oper- ated from 200 nm to 600 nm. Attained data was processed by MassLynxV4.1 software (Waters Corporation, MA, USA). Principal component analysis (PCA) was performed by XLSTAT software 5.03 2.6 | Mapping target compounds by DI‐SPME‐LC‐MS Mapping extraction experiments followed the same protocol as previ- ously described (Figure S1 in the Supporting Information). The actinobacteria culture was divided into eight equal parts at a 45° angle, and each fiber was spaced by 0.7 cm in the same axis. In total, 49 experiments were performed simultaneously in the actinobacteria culture following the Cartesian and Polar plan (Figure S1). In the polar plan, the angle (θ) and radius (r) were adjusted from the center point to

maintain a spacing of 0.7 cm for each fiber. Cartesian coordinates were converted into Polar coordinates via the Pythagoras Theorem, using the tangent θ.38,39 The plots were generated in Origin 9.0 soft- ware (OriginLab Corporation®, MA, USA). Coated glasstip emitters (1.0 mm O. D, and 0.58 mm I.D) were acquired from New Objective (New Objective Inc., MA, USA). The in‐house ion- ization source used for direct coupling was built at the machine shop of the Universidade de São Paulo, Faculdade de Filosofia, Ciências e Letras de Ribeirão Preto (Ribeirao Preto, Sao Paulo, Brazil). This in‐house ioni- zation source enabled precise placement of the emitter in front of the mass spectrometer entrance, and the 3D‐moving stage allowed for position adjustments along the three axes (X, Y, and Z). The loaded emitter was placed at a distance of 2.5 mm from the ion transfer capil- lary. Following DI‐SPME from actinobacteria culture (extraction and rinsing procedures followed the same protocol as described in the pre- vious section), the fiber was placed into the emitter device preloaded with 5 μl of desorption solvent (acetonitrile/water, 75:25 v/v—0.1 % of formic acid) for 4 min. As an integrated sample prepa- ration strategy, SPME minimizes matrix effects due to its superior cleanup capabilities, leading to higher sensitivity in analysis. Further, the versatility of SPME, which offers multiple geometries, allows for easy direct coupling of the technique to mass spectrometry instru- mentation.
